<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Educational Affairs Department -- Heritage</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><IMG SRC="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></a></center>
<P>
<H2>Educational Affairs Department</H2>
<HR>
<P>
 The Educational Affairs department includes <A HREF="/heritage/p_review/">
 <I>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</I></A>,
the quarterly journal of The Heritage Foundation, <A
HREF="/heritage/dept_writeups/95lect.html">Lectures and
Seminars</A>, and Academic Programs. The Heritage Foundation's academic
programs are intended to encourage the interchange of ideas between
scholars and policymakers, while building a national network of
conservative scholars and educational leaders committed to academic
excellence and the principles of liberty and constitutional order.
<P>
<B>The Bradley Fellows Program</B>
<P>
 The Bradley Fellows Program at The Heritage Foundation is intended
to enable scholars and academically rigorous journalists to conduct
a long-term research project in Washington, D.C., and to produce
a book important to the future of the conservative movement. 

<P>
 Each author is in residence at The Heritage Foundation for one
academic year, during which time he or she is expected to complete
all or most of their book.  In addition to their individual research
projects, Bradley Scholars hold roundtable discussions at Heritage,
and add their academic expertise to Heritage's general intellectual
environment. Each Bradley Fellow will receive a one year stipend,
plus funds to cover expenses and materials needed to support their
work.  During and after the scholar's residency at Heritage, our
marketing departments will communicate the author's ideas to Capitol
Hill and the media.  Books are to be published commercially.
<P>
 Current Bradley Fellows are writing on practical solutions to
the crime problem in American neighborhoods, black churches that
are successfully strengthening local communities; and a conservative
model of corporate social responsibility. The Heritage Foundation
is currently interested in supporting work in, but not necessarily
limited to, the following six subject areas: How Immigrants Become
Americans (An examination of the institutions that historically
assimilated foreigners into the American mainstream); The Economic
Revival of Communities (A look at communities whose economies
have revived after terrible social and economic setbacks ); The
Other Washington (An examination of civil society in Washington,
D.C. in the shadow of both federal and city government bureaucracy);
The Case for Raising the Retirement Age (Examining the economic
and medical benefits of a later retirement age); Family, City,
State, Nation (A major philosophical work, written for a large
audience, that would explore which areas of policy are appropriate
for the federal government, which should be left for state government,
which for local government, and which shouldn't be handled by
government at all); Alternatives to Federal Funding of Scientific
Research; and Alternatives to Federal Funding of the Arts.
<P>
 The Bradley Fellows are chosen in an informal competition, based
on individual qualifications and project proposals.  Please direct
further questions or mail your proposal directly to the Manager
of Academic Programs at The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002.  The Bradley Program is
made possible by a grant from the Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation
of Milwaukee, Wisconsin.
<P>
<B>The Salvatori Fellows Program</B>
<P>
 Through the Salvatori Center for Academic Leadership, The Heritage
Foundation assists those faculty and educational leaders who are
committed to the renewal of academic excellence and the recovery
of our nation's founding principles so as to encourage an enlightened
patriotism and bolster the foundations of liberty in America.
<P>
 Each year the Salvatori Center selects twenty-five young faculty
and doctoral candidates in the social sciences and the humanities
to participate in a ten-day summer colloquium which takes place
in Washington, D.C., entitled &quot;The Foundations of American
Liberty.&quot;  The colloquium examines the fundamental principles
of American constitutionalism as articulated in the important
documents of the founding era.  In addition, the colloquium considers
the history and present workings of our political institutions
-- the Congress, the courts, the presidency and the executive
branch bureaucracy, the two-party system -- as a means of better
understanding the principles underlying contemporary political
issues.  It includes meetings with congressional leaders and other
policymakers to study the role of ideas in public affairs and
the character of political leadership in American society.
<P>
 Each Salvatori Fellow receives an honorarium, travel expenses,
and a per diem allowance as a participant in the colloquium. 
After the completion of the program, Fellows will continue their
affiliation with The Heritage Foundation as members of a national
network of adjunct scholars, colleagues in the ongoing work of
reclaiming our educational institutions and enlivening the public
discussion of American principles. 
<P>
 For application information, please call write to the Manager
of Academic Programs, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002.  Applications require a
vita, references, a writing sample and a pr&eacute;cis of the
dissertation (for Ph.D. candidates).  The application and attachments
are due by February 15. The Salvatori Program is made possible
by a grant from the Henry Salvatori Foundation of Los Angeles,
California.
<P>
<a href="/heritage/intern_program/intern.html"><B>The Heritage Internship Program</B></a>
<P>
 The Heritage Intern Program is intended to introduce bright and
innovative college students to the policy-making process, involve
them in the important questions and issues of the day and encourage
them to become active and effective participants in public affairs.

<P>
 Each summer, The Heritage Foundation selects approximately forty
interns to work full-time in various departments for ten weeks,
receiving a weekly salary.  During the academic year a smaller
number of college students are chosen to work either part or full-time
in various departments, receiving a per diem stipend.
<P>
Departments offering internships: Academic Programs, The  Asian
Studies Center ,  Business Relations , Coalition Relations,  Domestic
and Economic Policy Studies , Educational Affairs,  Foreign and
Defense Policy Studies ,  Government Relations ,  Lectures and
Seminars , The New Majority Project, <A HREF="/heritage/p_review/">
 <I>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship </I></A>,  Public
Relations , and the Executive Offices of The Heritage Foundation.
<P>
 Internships vary depending on the department to which the participant
is assigned.  In general, applicants should posses strong writing
abilities, a talent for research and excellent communication skills.
 During the internship program, participants will attend weekly
discussion seminars on policy issues and conservative thought
that are designed to augment their day-to-day activities.  In
order to further enrich the internship experience, program participants
are invited and encouraged to attend Heritage Foundation lectures
and policy-briefings.  
<P>
 For application information, please call <a href="mailto: personsb@heritage.org">Beth Persons</a> at (202) 546-4400, or write to Intern Coordinator, Academic Programs, The Heritage
Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002.
The application also requires a resume, a short statement, a writing
sample and two letters of application. Applications and attachments
for summer internships are accepted between January 1 and March
1.  They are due for the Fall semester by August 15, and for the
Spring semester by December 15.
<P>
<B>Congress and the Constitution Seminars</B>
<P>
 Congress and the Constitution is a bi-weekly series of luncheon
seminars hosted by The Heritage Foundation and The Federalist
Society that take place on Capitol Hill thanks to the sponsorship
of Representative Charles Canady, Chairman of the House Subcommittee
on the Constitution. The purpose of these seminars is to familiarize
interested House and Senate members and key congressional staff
with a wide variety of issues that serve as a framework for the
public discussion of constitutional questions, and for the consideration
of proposed legislation, business before committees, floor debate
on key issues, etc.  Seminars are conducted by prominent legal
scholars and constitutional experts, and last approximately one
and a half hours.  Lecturers speak for about fifteen minutes each,
followed by group discussion.  Participants receive written materials
to supplement the seminar.  A working luncheon is provided.  
<P>
 Recent topics and speakers have included: &quot;Property Rights
And The Fifth Amendment&quot; with Roger Clegg of the National
Legal Center for the Public Interest and Roger Marzulla, Former
US Assistant Attorney General; &quot;Congressional Accountability
Under The Law&quot; with Walter Berns, American Enterprise Institute
and Professor Nelson Lund of George Mason University School of
Law; &quot;Congressional Oversight &amp; Separation Of Powers&quot;
with Douglas Cox, Former US Deputy Assistant Attorney General
and Theodore B. Olson, Former US Assistant Attorney General; &quot;Federalism
And Enumerated Powers&quot; with Timothy Flanigan, Former US Assistant
Attorney General; and Gregory Katsas, Associate, Jones, Day, Reavis
&amp; Pogue; &quot;Race and the Constitution: Civil Rights, Affirmative
Action and the Fourteenth Amendment&quot; with Clint Bolick, Vice
President, Institute for Justice, Michael Carvin, Former U.S.
Deputy Assistant Attorney General, and Michael Greve, Exec. Director,
Center for Individual Rights; &quot;Does Congress Speak for the
Constitution? Congress and Constitutional Interpretation&quot;
with Timothy Flanigan, Former US Assistant Attorney General, and
James Gouch, Former Assistant to the U.S. Solicitor General; and
&quot;Crime and Punishment in America: What Can Congress Do?&quot;
with  <a href="/heritage/staff/meese.htm">Edwin Meese III</a> , Former U.S. Attorney General.
<P>
 Members of Congress and their staff who are interested in obtaining
more information about these seminars should contact the Manager
of Academic Programs, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts
Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002.
<p>
<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/thpubs.html">To Order Heritage Foundation
Publications</a>
